Here some of them have found two sacraments; one, of God and the soul, in the man and woman when betrothed; the other, of Christ and the Church, in the husband and wife. The conjugal intercourse, upon their principles, however, is a sacrament, from which no Christian ought to be prohibited; unless the sacraments os Christiana are so incompatible, that they cannot consist together. There is also another absurdity in their doctrine. They affirm that the grace of the Holy Spirit is conferred in every sacrament 3 they acknowledge that the conjugal intercourse is a sacrament3 yet they deny that the Holy Spirit is ever present in that intercourse.

XXXVII. For, when they had once established this notiori, they assumed to themselves the cognizanee os matrimonial causes; for matrimony was a spiritual thing, and not to be meddled with before lay judges.
